    <summary type="html">&lt;p&gt;Lookup tables (LUTs) are an important resource for systems programming. 
They are the embodiment of the time-space tradeoff: precomputing results allow faster computation, up to O(1)!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;My background: I‚Äôm a modern C++ enthusiast and a embedded systems developer. Recently, I had to implement two CRC tables, with different parameters. Instead of hard coding the tables, I went for my favorite kind of approach: computed at compile time. As the codebase was in C++11, it reminded me how far we‚Äôve come.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So, in this article, we‚Äôll review how to implement compile-time lookup tables in C++, for every Standard C++ published so far: C++98, C++03, C++11, C++14, C++17 and C++20. We‚Äôll focus on the evolution of &lt;code&gt;constexpr&lt;/code&gt;, but we‚Äôll also see important additions to the language, such as &lt;code&gt;auto&lt;/code&gt; and library functionality.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Note&lt;/strong&gt;: for this article, we‚Äôll only consider features available on each Standard, even if some of the library features were possible to implement in previous versions of C++.&lt;/p&gt;
